help on to get you started:

GETTING STARTED - The basics of Avendar and MUDding in general.
INFORMATION - How to get info on yourself and your surroundings.
MOVEMENT - How to move around in the world of Avendar.
INTERACTION - How to interact with objects and items in Avendar.
COMMUNICATION - How to communicate with others in Avendar.
COMBAT - How to engage (and survive!) combat in Avendar.

Be sure to pay attention to the \#See Also\# located at the bottom of
many of the helpfiles, as they often point to other useful pieces of
information on the topic you\@re reading on.

If you are stuck or confused and cannot find help on a certain topic,
please read \@help PRAY\@ for instructions on how to contact an immortal
who may be able to help you.


/---------------------------------------------------------------------\\
|                              MOVEMENT                               |
\\---------------------------------------------------------------------/

Avendar consists of \@rooms\@, through which you may traverse.  The
basic commands for doing so represent the directions in which you
may move:

north, east, south, west, up, down

Typing any of these (or simply the first letter thereof) will move
your character in the specified direction, so long as there is an
associated exit in the direction you are attempting to move.  You
can determine the valid exits from a room by observing the list that
is displayed by default whenever you enter a new location, which
appears below the room description, looking something like:

[Exits: east up]

You may also view the exits from a room by typing \@exits\@, which will
give you a more descriptive explanation of the connecting rooms.
(Note: If the above exit information is not being displayed upon
entering new rooms, you may have accidently turned this display off.
Type \@autoexit\@ to turn the function back on.)

At times you may need to open a door in order to be able to proceed
in a direction.  Exits with closed doors do not appear in the exit
list until they have been opened, so be sure to read room descriptions
carefully, as that is the only way of making sure you\@re not missing
something!  In order to open a door, simply type \@open <direction>\@.
Once again, direction may be specified by simply the first letter.
If the door is locked, and you have the appropriate key, you may first
unlock the door by typing \@unlock <direction>\@.  As well, doors may
be closed and locked with the \@close\@ and \@lock\@ commands,
respectively.

Now you have the basics of moving around in the land of Avendar.  You
will also want to view the helps below to learn more:

See also: RECALL, POSITIONS


/---------------------------------------------------------------------\\
|                              POSITIONS                              |
\\---------------------------------------------------------------------/

While travelling in Avendar, you can assume a number of different
positions, from sitting, to standing, to lying down.  The basic
commands for changing position are:

sleep, rest, sit, stand

When sleeping or resting, you will regain your health, mana, and
movement more quickly, but you are restricted in the actions you
may perform in each state.  When sleeping you will regenerate more
quickly than when resting, and cannot see your surroundings.

As well, if there is an object in the room that allows it, you may
use any above the above commands with an optional <target> to 
assume that position on or by the object.  For example:

\@sleep bedroll\@
You go to sleep on a thick bedroll.


/---------------------------------------------------------------------\\
|                               RECALL                                |
\\---------------------------------------------------------------------/

Syntax: \@recall\@ (or /)

The \@recall\@ command may be used by characters of level 10 or less,
by people in a ghostly state, or by druids with an existing circle of
stones.

Recall prays to the appropriate gods or nature spirits for miraculous
transportation from where you are back to the appropriate temple of
your hometown, or stone circle.

\@/\@ is a synonym for \@recall\@.

Recall costs half of your movement points.

Recall doesn\@t work in certain god-forsaken rooms.  Characters
afflicted by certain curses may not recall at all.

You may not recall from the middle of battle, or while your adrenaline
is gushing from combat.

See also: \@WORD OF RECALL\@, SPIRITRECALL


/---------------------------------------------------------------------\\
|                            COMMUNICATION                            |
\\---------------------------------------------------------------------/

Communication is the most essential part of your interactions in
Avendar.  You may communicate with others in a number of different
ways, to express yourself in the role you have chosen.  Bear in mind
that all communication while in Avendar should be In Character (in
other words, in the role of your character), unless you are using the
\@ooc\@ chat channel.  The basic commands used for communicating are:

say, esay, tell, gtell, yell, think, emote, pmote, smote, ooc

Please view the helps for the above commands for details on their
usages.

As well, certain characters will have access to the following
communication commands:

dt (for druids using \@commune with nature\@), sing (for bards), and
ht/house (for characters who are members of one of Avendar\@s houses)

See also: ROLEPLAYING, PRAY, NOTE
